column1: Who will win the 2020 Washington Democratic primary?
column5: ['Joe Biden', 'Pete Buttigieg', 'Amy Klobuchar', 'Bernie Sanders', 'Elizabeth Warren', 'Someone else', 'Michael Bloomberg']
column6: ['US Politics', 'Elections and Referenda']
Tight polls. Going to be a close one.
tweaking a bit, this is one of Sanders's strongest states left. But Biden up +1 and +3 in the last two polls.
Sanders still has a chance to win several states after super Tuesday, Washington he won big in 2016, so here he has better chance. But he will not do as well as in 2016.
Former Vice President Biden is closing strong, showing a narrow lead in the last two polls out of Washington.

This now looks like it will be very close. The polling is close but there are still a high percentage of undecideds, who seem to be breaking for Biden, so he might just edge it. On the other hand, the lateness of Biden's surge is to Sander's benefit because of mail voting that has taken place for the last couple of weeks.
Using 438 as baseline: https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/2020-primary-forecast/washington/

We've had a few more polls and as expected the chances of a Biden win have risen considerably. It's still difficult to tell them apart though. Although the polls give Biden a slight edge they still factor in support for Warren, since Warren has now withdrawn you would expect much of her support to go to Sanders. So 50-50.
it's woulde be sad, wenn Sanders can't win even washington.
Updating with new 538 forecast

RealClearPolitics poll average has Bernie up by 8. https://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2020/president/wa/washington_democratic_primary-7005.html FiveThirtyEight has Bernie rated as a 78% favorite. https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/2020-primary-forecast/washington/
Updating to incorporate Super Tuesday results
Using Prediction Market [https://www.predictit.org/markets/detail/6041].

What with the dropouts and a scarcity of polls it is proving difficult to get a grip of what could happen in this state. From the few polls we've had it looks like Sanders has a slight advantage. But these polls were done before SC and Super Tuesday and I think we can assume any lead he had has been cut.
Raised Joe Biden after Super Tuesday
Sanders isn't 100% mostly because he could have a health issue between now and then.

Elway Research polling from Feb. 15-18 shows Bernie Sanders polling at 21% and Joe Biden polling far behind at 10%, however a previous poll in January by Survey USA had Sanders at 26% and Biden at 21%. What improves Biden's odds is Mayor Buttigieg dropping from the race. Pete Buttigieg polled 8% and 9% in the past two polls; most of Mayor Buttigieg's moderate voters are likely to vote for Biden which may give him the push he needs to overcome Sanders, especially after Biden's recent win in South Carolina.
Adjusting in light of Buttigieg dropping out.
Updating due to Buttigieg Dropping
As a more liberal state, Washington should go for Sanders, with Warren an outside choice should Sanders falter.
Updating with new prior after 538 has incorporated this weekend's results.

roughly per 538, more bullish on Sanders.

Bernie easily won the Washington Primary against Hillary, and due to his momentum and lead in the 2020 primary, it seems inconceivable that he could lose in Washington.
